						               													<description>From the publisher:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;Jacob Marley is alive and well. And what&amp;rsquo;s more, he&amp;rsquo;s the boss of you.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;You&amp;rsquo;re a lowly clerk in young Jacob Marley&amp;rsquo;s powerful investment firm, which lends money to needs people throughout the city of London. Marley has decided to elevate one lucky clerk to the status of &amp;ldquo;friend,&amp;rdquo; meaning a partnership in Marley&amp;rsquo;s business, a handsome promotion, and Marley&amp;rsquo;s lifetime friendship. He&amp;rsquo;ll even get you out of Hell if you manage to outlive him. Such a deal!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;To make the most points with the boss, you must lend his money to the most trustworthy clients, and stay away from the ones that will ruin you. If you&amp;rsquo;re lucky, you&amp;rsquo;ll even grow up to be as stingy and horrible as he is.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;Jacob Marley, Esquire is a banking game with all the fun and excitement that implies. No, seriously, it&amp;rsquo;s good.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;quot;As a clerk in Marley&amp;rsquo;s investment firm, you are given an account of &amp;pound;12 to lend to various ne&amp;rsquo;er-do-well clients in London. Each turn, you move Marley through the streets of the city, randomly affecting the economy of London with a cool Economy Chart. Then you can see what&amp;rsquo;s going on in the street where Marley stopped. Will you lend your money to a lawyer, a financial institution, or a petty criminal? The choice is yours, but make sure you&amp;rsquo;re not the only player with a client like this, or it can cost you a bundle of money and points!&amp;quot;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The version which was subsequently published is significantly different, and (claims Cheapass, with some justification) much improved.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
